Three herons were seen and heard flying south to north on migration in an urban setting. In the field one of the calls sounded drier and raspier. Upon closer inspection of the recording, obtained via a "nocmig" sound-trap that night, it was clear that one of the herons was in fact a Purple Heron; the bird heard calling first in the clip. The sonogram (see full) is also different, with the notes less visible, in comparison to grey.

-6dB highpass filter at 750Hz + -8dB noise reduction overall afterwards. Only the best series of calls from several series with identical calls (with no apparent variation between them).
The individual has been present for at least a month, apparently roosting close to the recording spot given call series heard both first and last thing on a couple of days, but not during the rest of the day. Despite being surprisingly elusive until now, I finally managed to both record and see it before sunrise. Given the poor light and the bird remaining in cover (western holm oak and young stone pine trees) throughout, all I could see was a rather green 'common' chiffchaff and the identification is based on call characteristics.

 Ave realiza su canto desde lo alto de un farallón rocoso, el hábitat está compuesto por pastizales de montaña salpicados de matorrales de Piorno serrano (Cytisus oromediterraneus ) y Cambroño ( Adenocarpus hispanicus)
Se ha reducido el intervalo de tiempo entre las frases de la canción.
Edición de audio: Reducción de ruido con Audacity.

Hybrid family
Adult male: Mixed singer (Black Redstart x Common Redstart). Alternates the songs of both species (mostly singong like Black redstart) with an accelerated tempo when singing as a Black Redstart. phoenicurus-type whistled call (Western vocal type), phoenicurus-type takking call, phoenicurus-type interaction calls. Spacing of P6-P5 shorter than P6-P7, P6 not emarginated. Axillaries orange. Looks like a Common Redstart.

Adult female: Presumed pure female Black Redstart ssp gibraltariensis. gibraltariensis-type whistled calls, gibraltariensis-type takking calls. (Spacing P6-P7)/(Spacing P6-P5) = 2.2, clear emargination on P6.

2 immatures : Hybrids of the male mixed-singer Common Redstart and a female Black Redstart. Whistled calls of the gibraltariensis type, taking calls calls of the gibraltariensis type, (Spacing P6-P7)/(Spacing P6-P5) varying from 1.2 to 2 depending on the individual. Weak emargination on P6.

Comparatif des cris de vol nocturne du Gobemouche noir. Compilation de plusieurs dizaines de cris enregistrés ces 4 dernières années en migration nocturne en Ile-de-France. Les cris sont rapprochés les uns des autres pour pouvoir être comparés visuellement. Une comparaison auditive sera plus efficace en ralentissant la vitesse du son (x0.1 à x 0.3 par exemple). Il y a là tout le panel des cris de vol nocturne (très variés !) du Gobemouche noir. Vers la fin vous trouverez plus particulièrement les enchaînements "zezz-----wit", plus rarement poussés mais typiques. Dans ces cas-là (seulement) nous avons respecté la distance entre les cris, distance qui là est aussi un critère d'identification. Nous avons laissé exprès beaucoup de cris très faibles car vous y serez confronté régulièrement et tous ces cris faibles identifiés  ici de manière certaine vous aideront ...à identifier les vôtres !

Différents exemples d'effets indésirables de l'écho rassemblés ici en un son. Tout d'abord deux cris de Petits Gravelots, qui sont chacun dédoublés. 
Puis un cri de Foulque macroule, dédoublé aussi. 
Ensuite un cri de Chouette hulotte qui est à la fois dédoublé mais surtout rendu indistinct par les traînées dues elles aussi à l'écho (cette fois-ci dans un milieu "trop" boisé"). 
Enfin un cri de Rougegorge familier où l'on voit de même des traînées (idem, milieu "trop" boisé").
Both Grasshopper warbler
At night recording : 3 species migrating together, one of them can be Black-tailed Godwit most presumably ; should it be confirm or can it be Bar-tailed Godwit ?

#Reuploaded-Soundscape#

**Bandpass : 1500 - 9500 Hz**

The first upload did not show any sonogram here is a better version with sonogram. Species identified so far with the help of [Camille Vacher](https://xeno-canto.org/contributor/LTIHWHLJQI)  in order of apparition : _Cyanistes caeruleus_ (high pitch descending repetitive calls), _Fringilla coelebs_ interrupted by _Phylloscopus collybita_ then maybe _Buteo buteo_ in the background then _Parus major_.

Comparatif de "tew" et de "tslew" de Bruant ortolan enregistrés ces 4 dernières années en migration nocturne en Ile-de-France. Ces deux types de cris sont proches et il y a entre eux beaucoup de cris "transitionnels" qui les "relient" en quelques sorte. C'est pour cette raison que nous les avons mis sur un seul fichier son, mêlés en quelque sorte, en essayant tout de même de les regrouper par "familles". On passe donc le long de cette "frise" d'un cris à l'autre plusieurs fois au gré de tous les cris intermédiaires qui se rencontrent très fréquemment. Les cris sont très rapprochés les uns des autres  pour pouvoir être comparés visuellement. Une comparaison auditive sera plus efficace en ralentissant la vitesse du son (x0.1 par exemple). Audio mixed in post in Reaper: main audio track is Reed Warbler with edited shortened intervals between vocalizations - underneath this I've mixed the separately-recorded sound of a nearby small water trickle where the pond drains off excess water.
The intervals between vocalizations were often full of heavy aircraft noise, so I removed them.
In one or two places in the uploaded track you can hear these still there as I could not get rid of them without compromising the bird vocalization.
It may have been coincidence but it seemed almost as if the bird sang more enthusiastically whenever an aircraft flew low overhead (this location is very near Heathrow Airport and on the flight path for take-offs and landings).

There were two male Reed Warblers at opposite sides of the Peg's Pond, about 20m apart, both singing across the water to each other from within fairly recently planted reed beds.
A path runs round the perimeter of the pond, and I was able to move to within about 5m of one of the Reed Warblers as it flitted about the reeds singing intermittently. After a while I spotted it and could track it visually quite easily. It climbed at one point to the top of one of the reeds and was almost fully visible to me.

Weather was fine and bright, about 1 hour after sunrise, the dampness slowly evaporating off the ground.

Drumming (sonation) from a single captive male Southern Oak Bush-cricket (Meconema meridionale) in a terrarium at night.
A series of 3-8 abrupt (100ms), low frequency sounds (0.1-1.4 kHz) produced from the male tapping its hind leg on Ivy leaves in the presence of a female. At peak activity it produced 11 drumming bursts in one minute (at 25.1°C ambient room temp). Drumming bursts lasting between 0.8 and 3.6 secs.
Note: the volume here has been increased in the processed sound file, but the tapping was actually audible across the room under near-silent conditions.
Calling song/stridulation from a male Southern Sickle-bearing Bush-cricket (Phaneroptera nana) in insectarium at 23:34h (25.4°C).
Exceptional year for this species, spreading far from the core breeding site at Rainham Landfill. Females attracted to moth trap light. Many nymphs found.
